WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.640 --> 00:00:04.550
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: What does organic mean anymore?

00:00:04.550 --> 00:00:08.820
Tales from the front lines of the movement
and just to give you a little bit of background

00:00:08.820 --> 00:00:13.660
on who Bob Scowcroft is is basically he's
an activist.

00:00:13.660 --> 00:00:17.390
He first joined the environmental movement
to work on the Alaskan Native Claims Settlement

00:00:17.390 --> 00:00:23.249
Act in the early 1970s and later became a
national organizer on pesticide issues for

00:00:23.249 --> 00:00:25.170
the Friends of the Earth.

00:00:25.170 --> 00:00:30.470
As organizer for the FOE, he set up table
at the Natural Food's Agent Orange because

00:00:30.470 --> 00:00:34.149
of the drift of that herbicide on nearby farms.

00:00:34.149 --> 00:00:40.309
And basically from there, um, Barney Brickman
and 2 other organizers from the California

00:00:40.309 --> 00:00:46.090
certified organic farmers came and paid him
a visit to his table and introduced Scowcroft

00:00:46.090 --> 00:00:51.489
to the organi, organic farming movement and
since then he became the first professional

00:00:51.489 --> 00:00:57.510
environmentalist to attend and present at
the ecological farming conference.

00:00:57.510 --> 00:01:00.460
Then held at a muddy church camp in the Santa
Cruz Mountains.

00:01:00.460 --> 00:01:06.000
&gt;&gt;Presenter 2: Hi everyone, I'm Liv and I'm
a chef.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:09.110
And I'm just delighted to have my friend Bob
here.

00:01:09.110 --> 00:01:12.230
I met him at the EcoFarmConference.

00:01:12.230 --> 00:01:20.820
So, 15 years after I interviewed him as a
reporter when I was in Chicago, so thank you

00:01:20.820 --> 00:01:21.820
for coming.

00:01:21.820 --> 00:01:22.820
&gt;&gt;Bob Scowcroft: You're welcome.

00:01:22.820 --> 00:01:27.830
&gt;&gt;Presenter 2: Bob is quite a story teller
and raconteur so I'm, we're just gonna be

00:01:27.830 --> 00:01:29.950
pretend it's not summer and it's winter.

00:01:29.950 --> 00:01:34.780
We've got our feet pulled up to the fire and
I'm just gonna ask a few questions and I think

00:01:34.780 --> 00:01:35.780
he'll just go.

00:01:35.780 --> 00:01:38.579
So, that was a long time ago.

00:01:38.579 --> 00:01:43.350
&gt;&gt;Bob Scowcroft: Yes, that video was shot
it 1989.

00:01:43.350 --> 00:01:49.700
He noted that organic was about 1 percent
of the food economy.

00:01:49.700 --> 00:01:59.799
We are 23 years later and thousands of articles
and reporters and chefs, organic's now 4 percent

00:01:59.799 --> 00:02:03.289
of the economy.

00:02:03.289 --> 00:02:08.610
When I joined CCOF I was the first full time
employee and director, there were 178 farmers

00:02:08.610 --> 00:02:10.229
in the program.

00:02:10.229 --> 00:02:14.180
When I left there were 780 farmers in the
program.

00:02:14.180 --> 00:02:21.740
During the 5 years that I was at CCOF, actually
I'm just gonna step back and say, to give

00:02:21.740 --> 00:02:27.560
you a sense of the history of organic, it
started to be written about in the 20s and

00:02:27.560 --> 00:02:30.890
30s, both in Japan and in the UK.

00:02:30.890 --> 00:02:35.760
Rodale really brought it to the US in 1947,
first publication of Organic Gardening.

00:02:35.760 --> 00:02:42.080
But, Mokichi Okada in Japan and Sir Albert
Howard and Lady Balfour, Lady Balfour is the

00:02:42.080 --> 00:02:47.190
key, you know, royalty is what it is; she
was interested about the soils so she started

00:02:47.190 --> 00:02:50.739
a soil association in the 20s over there in
the UK.

00:02:50.739 --> 00:02:53.500
So this, to this day we hear that it's a fad.

00:02:53.500 --> 00:03:00.500
Well, we're getting on almost 100 years, 80-90
years; I think the fad part a really mute

00:03:00.500 --> 00:03:01.790
point now.

00:03:01.790 --> 00:03:04.370
But the first regulation was written in Oregon
in 1974.

00:03:04.370 --> 00:03:12.620
The first law, actual law, was in California
in 1978; it was a 2 page law and Ag so disliked

00:03:12.620 --> 00:03:16.299
the word organic that the only way they could
get it passed was to make into the health

00:03:16.299 --> 00:03:17.629
and nutrition program.

00:03:17.629 --> 00:03:18.980
I'm not sure if you knew that.

00:03:18.980 --> 00:03:25.170
And California health and safety code was
where the first organic food act was parked

00:03:25.170 --> 00:03:32.150
and it had no enforcement, it was 2 pages
long but it did define the simplistic no synthetic

00:03:32.150 --> 00:03:37.930
devotion to natural crop rotation; the very
basics of what organic had started out.

00:03:37.930 --> 00:03:44.220
So by '89 with Alar, which was, to this day
they call it the Alar scare.

00:03:44.220 --> 00:03:50.019
I very strongly point out it was not a scare,
it was carcinogenic and it was taken off the

00:03:50.019 --> 00:03:54.930
market 6 months after CBS' 60 Minutes did
the story on it.

00:03:54.930 --> 00:03:58.760
But it took Meryl Streep to bring attention
to it.

00:03:58.760 --> 00:04:05.079
Environmentalists had been working on it for
a decade but it was Meryl Streep in the, on

00:04:05.079 --> 00:04:09.829
a couple of TV talk shows, the power of talk
shows, that brought it to attention.

00:04:09.829 --> 00:04:18.080
So, CCOF rewrote the California law for enforcement
and then a year later, thanks to Senator Leahy,

00:04:18.080 --> 00:04:24.260
7 people got together and said we've written
the California law, we have friends in Oregon,

00:04:24.260 --> 00:04:31.940
we have friends in New England, a couple in
Ohio, let's write a national law.

00:04:31.940 --> 00:04:33.740
Little did we know what we were getting into.

00:04:33.740 --> 00:04:40.130
But, for the power of individual and the power
of very small group, I think this is a particularly

00:04:40.130 --> 00:04:42.290
critical story to tell.

00:04:42.290 --> 00:04:47.910
That to this day, 7 to 10 people dedicated
and with a vision can get together and can

00:04:47.910 --> 00:04:50.390
make global change.

00:04:50.390 --> 00:04:51.520
Never forget that.

00:04:51.520 --> 00:04:52.620
It's happened here.

00:04:52.620 --> 00:04:54.140
It happens in a lot of places.

00:04:54.140 --> 00:04:57.500
&gt;&gt;Presenter 2: So that was 1 percent of the
market.

00:04:57.500 --> 00:04:58.570
We're now at 4 percent?

00:04:58.570 --> 00:05:00.710
&gt;&gt;Bob Scowcroft: Little over 4, 4.2, 4.3

00:05:00.710 --> 00:05:03.390
&gt;&gt;Presenter 2: So I'm gonna ask the question
from the other side.

00:05:03.390 --> 00:05:04.390
Why so slow?

00:05:04.390 --> 00:05:07.460
Why so, what's, what have been the impediments?

00:05:07.460 --> 00:05:15.360
&gt;&gt;Bob Scowcroft: Um, uh, absolute to this
day, resistance from the agro industrial food

00:05:15.360 --> 00:05:21.530
system and it's an integrated system, crop
insurance; you can't get organic crop insurance

00:05:21.530 --> 00:05:26.900
to organic research; you can't get that to
scale.

00:05:26.900 --> 00:05:33.000
Now there's 4 supermarkets and 3 box stores
that represent something like 70, 7 buyers

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:37.491
in United States purchase between 70 and 80
percent of all our food.

00:05:37.491 --> 00:05:38.491
7 buyers.

00:05:38.491 --> 00:05:39.940
&gt;&gt;male #1: All food or organic?

00:05:39.940 --> 00:05:45.300
&gt;&gt;Bob Scowcroft: All food total comes through
7 buyers.

00:05:45.300 --> 00:05:52.690
Now, it's like, in California there are 2,200
organic farms, 2 of them, and I said earlier

00:05:52.690 --> 00:05:58.840
in a meeting I'm gonna try not to use brand
names, but 2 of them gross a billion dollars.

00:05:58.840 --> 00:06:01.030
And they sell into those 7.

00:06:01.030 --> 00:06:08.590
So economies of scale, very difficult for
organic to integrate into, um, research, organic

00:06:08.590 --> 00:06:11.500
pest management.

00:06:11.500 --> 00:06:15.200
The system of Ag research is really product
based.

00:06:15.200 --> 00:06:21.090
Actually, there was a law, this is a kind
of funny, well, depends on your Ag sense of

00:06:21.090 --> 00:06:26.540
humor, Birch Bayh and Bob Dole wrote a law
in the 80s called the" Bayh Dole Act"

00:06:26.540 --> 00:06:29.090
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Bob Scowcroft: It's not, everyone's gonna

00:06:29.090 --> 00:06:37.090
have pineapples but the "Bayh Dole Act" reformatted
the entire research system to be product based.

00:06:37.090 --> 00:06:43.530
That you could be a company and give money
into an Ag research program and dedicate a

00:06:43.530 --> 00:06:50.130
research question you have and you could profit,
i.e. patent, off that product that came out

00:06:50.130 --> 00:06:51.540
with academia.

00:06:51.540 --> 00:06:54.040
So, organic is information based.

00:06:54.040 --> 00:06:56.150
You can't really patent information.

00:06:56.150 --> 00:06:58.990
You can't, it's public domain activity.

00:06:58.990 --> 00:07:05.020
So, finding out when to release the ladybugs
or when to apply, when to harvest a cover

00:07:05.020 --> 00:07:08.550
crop, which cover crop works with which soil?

00:07:08.550 --> 00:07:15.270
That was a historic Ag research program from
our land grant system, from the late 1890s

00:07:15.270 --> 00:07:18.380
to the 1940s, that's what land grants did.

00:07:18.380 --> 00:07:26.070
And then in, after the agricultural chemicals
became very popular in the '70s, by the '80s

00:07:26.070 --> 00:07:31.420
the system, we wanted to cut funding for Government
waste and to Ag, we were wasting Government

00:07:31.420 --> 00:07:32.710
money to get information.

00:07:32.710 --> 00:07:39.070
So, instead, we wanted, by this act, to privatize
our Ag research system.

00:07:39.070 --> 00:07:44.440
So imagine how you're gonna get an organic
crop rotation system in place.

00:07:44.440 --> 00:07:49.990
I'd say that's very expensive, that's been
one of the main challenges is breaking that,

00:07:49.990 --> 00:07:56.210
and the other part is also economy of scale,
competitive price organic can be is very expensive

00:07:56.210 --> 00:08:00.620
in many parts of the country, you can't get
it year round in many parts of the country.

00:08:00.620 --> 00:08:06.710
So the first person with berries or some of
the other fruits and vegetables sell it for

00:08:06.710 --> 00:08:07.860
a lot of money.

00:08:07.860 --> 00:08:13.310
That's something called the capitalist system
where they make a very healthy profit.

00:08:13.310 --> 00:08:18.560
And, somehow, this is supposed to be, this
is supposed to be a negative to organic.

00:08:18.560 --> 00:08:24.320
Well, it's, uh, buyer and seller working it
out.

00:08:24.320 --> 00:08:26.500
Now, things have changed a little bit.

00:08:26.500 --> 00:08:32.450
After CCOF, 2 farmers and I decided, talk
about tilting against windmills, we decided

00:08:32.450 --> 00:08:37.260
that we were gonna change the grant making
program so we founded the Organic Farming

00:08:37.260 --> 00:08:44.710
Research Foundation so that we could make
grants but our grants were based on, uh, agreeing,

00:08:44.710 --> 00:08:50.121
upon receipt of money to not patent any information
that it was all, 100 percent, in the public

00:08:50.121 --> 00:08:57.400
domain and that we would fund ideas as well
as actual projects.

00:08:57.400 --> 00:09:03.060
And OFRF, I retired a year and a half ago,
I was the executive director for 20 years,

00:09:03.060 --> 00:09:10.500
the average lifespan of a, professional lifespan
of an E.D. is 3 to 5 years.

00:09:10.500 --> 00:09:18.470
So I was there 20 years and we made over 350
grants and many of those recipients are now

00:09:18.470 --> 00:09:23.840
professors and are now, finally, over 20 universities
have organic research programs.

00:09:23.840 --> 00:09:27.460
So, look how long it took us to get there.

00:09:27.460 --> 00:09:32.360
&gt;&gt;Presenter 2: What was the most difficult
part about getting the federal law written?

00:09:32.360 --> 00:09:40.950
&gt;&gt;Bob Scowcroft: Um, well, it's the opposition
of the agricultural industry; some of you

00:09:40.950 --> 00:09:44.750
may have a little bit of awareness that the
Farm Bill is front and center this summer.

00:09:44.750 --> 00:09:46.020
It's a really big deal.

00:09:46.020 --> 00:09:53.310
Well, in 1990 was an earlier Farm Bill, the
House Agriculture Committee refused to hold

00:09:53.310 --> 00:09:54.770
any hearings on organic.

00:09:54.770 --> 00:09:59.790
I was actually in a meeting in the mid '80s
in the USDA that a senior agency official

00:09:59.790 --> 00:10:04.680
came in and broke up the meeting 'cause a
communist sympathizer was there; that was

00:10:04.680 --> 00:10:05.680
me.

00:10:05.680 --> 00:10:07.830
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Bob Scowcroft: Supporting organic family

00:10:07.830 --> 00:10:10.660
farmers and I had to leave the building.

00:10:10.660 --> 00:10:15.640
That's the intensity of the passion at that
period of time.

00:10:15.640 --> 00:10:22.850
But, 1990, 5 years later, the House Ag Committee
refused to hold hearings so we actually had

00:10:22.850 --> 00:10:28.440
one congressman from Oregon, two actually
with Sam Farr, but really, Peter Defazio carried

00:10:28.440 --> 00:10:35.250
the bill on the floor of the house, no hearings,
no public testimony, no public comment.

00:10:35.250 --> 00:10:39.000
Senator Cranston and Senator Leahy carried
it in the Senate.

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:44.600
One hearing, one time and on the house it
was voted 198 to 189 and we won the amendment

00:10:44.600 --> 00:10:46.260
on the floor of the House.

00:10:46.260 --> 00:10:51.761
And we just pushed every grass roots button
we had and the law was 16 pages long and it

00:10:51.761 --> 00:10:57.410
required a National Organic Standards Board
which was the only advisory board that had

00:10:57.410 --> 00:11:01.860
the right to stop a bad action and to recommend
a good action.

00:11:01.860 --> 00:11:06.920
There are 29 advisory boards in the USDA,
only one has statutory power and that's the

00:11:06.920 --> 00:11:10.040
National Organic Standards Board.

00:11:10.040 --> 00:11:15.090
The administration at the time, and I have
to say including into the Clinton administration,

00:11:15.090 --> 00:11:18.520
never empowered the actual drafting of the
regulations.

00:11:18.520 --> 00:11:22.990
They were due 18 months after the passage
of the law; we got it 10 years.

00:11:22.990 --> 00:11:27.690
It took them 10 years to post the rules and
they were terrible.

00:11:27.690 --> 00:11:33.290
They suggested you could use genetic engineering;
you could put sewage sludge on organic farms

00:11:33.290 --> 00:11:38.190
as long as â€“, a number of pasture regulations
were terrible.

00:11:38.190 --> 00:11:42.060
They made a mistake, and actually this is
kind of a cool little computer story, it was

00:11:42.060 --> 00:11:48.190
the first rule ever published on the internet,
it was the USDA decided, they had this little

00:11:48.190 --> 00:11:51.580
corner thing, organic, no big deal and they
would publish it on the internet and ask for

00:11:51.580 --> 00:11:58.580
public testimony, the largest testimony they'd
ever received was animal welfare issues around

00:11:58.580 --> 00:12:04.570
production of veal which is a pretty lousy
way to, well we'll leave that for another

00:12:04.570 --> 00:12:08.340
topic, but that had gotten 35,000 letters.

00:12:08.340 --> 00:12:12.620
So they published the organic rules thinking
they'd get maybe a couple of thousand, we

00:12:12.620 --> 00:12:16.810
generated 325,000 responses.

00:12:16.810 --> 00:12:21.440
Working assets, now called CREDO Phone Company,
the largest single, it donated, it generated

00:12:21.440 --> 00:12:27.660
35,000 comments through their phone subscriber
base, into the rules.

00:12:27.660 --> 00:12:33.200
That was such a tsunami, ten times the comments
they'd ever received, that they had to rewrite

00:12:33.200 --> 00:12:39.680
the rules and then the press, I think we we're
probably in contact, Liv and I and many others,

00:12:39.680 --> 00:12:46.190
the press really caught wind of this major
embarrassment and made major organic hay about

00:12:46.190 --> 00:12:50.050
it and they went back and had to rewrite them
again.

00:12:50.050 --> 00:12:59.290
And, finally, in 2002, 580 pages of every
single thing you can and can't do around organic

00:12:59.290 --> 00:13:03.020
was published and approved with two exceptions.

00:13:03.020 --> 00:13:07.480
One was pasture, they didn't quite know how
to figure out what organic pasture and organic

00:13:07.480 --> 00:13:10.490
meat and dairy was and is.

00:13:10.490 --> 00:13:16.150
They just published the final rule there in
2010, 20 years later, and the other was the

00:13:16.150 --> 00:13:21.000
interface between recombinant DNA, genetically
engineered products and organic.

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:27.400
All they said was you can't use it and we
felt there was a lot of protocol behind pollution

00:13:27.400 --> 00:13:29.930
from that and some other issues.

00:13:29.930 --> 00:13:34.610
So, those of you that wanna get into organic,
you gotta start when you're 20 or 30 cause

00:13:34.610 --> 00:13:39.330
you're gonna take it from 4 percent to 50
percent you gotta be young, I think, well

00:13:39.330 --> 00:13:42.730
maybe I'll be on a roll for a couple more
years.

00:13:42.730 --> 00:13:44.260
&gt;&gt;Presenter 2: Really?

00:13:44.260 --> 00:13:46.630
Can we reach 50 percent?

00:13:46.630 --> 00:13:48.350
That would be astonishing.

00:13:48.350 --> 00:13:57.870
&gt;&gt;Bob Scowcroft: You know, I think the infrastructure
as immature as it is, has the capacity to

00:13:57.870 --> 00:14:05.230
do that understanding that organic transition
requires, one of the key threads is 3 years

00:14:05.230 --> 00:14:08.920
from the last application of a prohibited
material.

00:14:08.920 --> 00:14:13.680
So, if something happened and we had to go
organic, I believe essentially the body of

00:14:13.680 --> 00:14:18.960
knowledge is there in almost every crop and
commodity to farm it organically but the land

00:14:18.960 --> 00:14:19.960
isn't.

00:14:19.960 --> 00:14:25.750
And we don't want sod busted or marginal land
or wets lands taken out and farmed organically.

00:14:25.750 --> 00:14:32.160
We want the deep soil of the heartland farmed
that way but it's gonna take years, so I have

00:14:32.160 --> 00:14:42.910
a fear, it's been my experience that organic
in many cases has grown due to sensational

00:14:42.910 --> 00:14:49.730
pesticide stories for the most part, horrific
poisonings, drift, discovery or final proof

00:14:49.730 --> 00:14:53.420
of carcinogenic chemicals and people throw
up their hands, "That's it, I'm gonna buy

00:14:53.420 --> 00:14:54.420
organic.

00:14:54.420 --> 00:14:55.420
I don't care."

00:14:55.420 --> 00:15:00.660
So if we have some other more food safety,
food issue, stories coming down the pike the

00:15:00.660 --> 00:15:05.960
push for organic with that same peaks and
valleys that we had during Alar where apples

00:15:05.960 --> 00:15:11.690
went for 70 dollars a box that were 6 or 8
dollars a box, the size of that package before.

00:15:11.690 --> 00:15:20.660
I will say, going a little bit out on a limb
here, my sense is that relative to food issues

00:15:20.660 --> 00:15:26.050
and the things that I follow, that some of
the next frightening data that's just starting

00:15:26.050 --> 00:15:30.029
to be peer reviewed, when I say frightening
it's not somebody standing up on a screen

00:15:30.029 --> 00:15:35.640
and ruining a dinner party or in a public
speech, I'm talking about peer review science

00:15:35.640 --> 00:15:43.560
coming out of Academia, the abuse of antibiotics
and chemicals in our meat production should

00:15:43.560 --> 00:15:46.360
gray the hair on the back of everyone's head.

00:15:46.360 --> 00:15:50.460
And the stories are just beginning to come
out.

00:15:50.460 --> 00:15:59.680
Just recently, uh, and I can provide the link
later on if you wish, urine tract infections,

00:15:59.680 --> 00:16:02.810
there's dinner party topic for ya
[Laughter]

00:16:02.810 --> 00:16:08.370
&gt;&gt;Bob Scowcroft: had been tied to a certain
antibiotic overused in poultry production.

00:16:08.370 --> 00:16:13.330
They know this, medical schools have now proven
this and, yet, can we get that antibiotic

00:16:13.330 --> 00:16:14.330
out of poultry?

00:16:14.330 --> 00:16:20.140
They don't even, they want more research,
let's take, you know, the data's not really

00:16:20.140 --> 00:16:21.140
in yet.

00:16:21.140 --> 00:16:22.340
You know science; we need more studies in
the future.

00:16:22.340 --> 00:16:27.520
Far as I'm concerned that data's in and what
I've read about some of the chemicals, antibiotics

00:16:27.520 --> 00:16:35.460
in hog production, I only eat, I mean, I know
the meat I eat almost personally, not the

00:16:35.460 --> 00:16:36.460
chicken itself
[Laughter]

00:16:36.460 --> 00:16:38.620
&gt;&gt;Bob Scowcroft: but the producer that made
it.

00:16:38.620 --> 00:16:46.140
How do we transition, I guess is the, to get
the 50 percent, you need a government objective,

00:16:46.140 --> 00:16:51.800
you need a massive investment in research
and, of course, you need the consumer that's

00:16:51.800 --> 00:16:57.610
gonna be paying those higher prices, in some
cases, some seasons, to support it.

00:16:57.610 --> 00:17:04.079
&gt;&gt;Presenter 2: We're close to 50 percent with
the Google culinary purchasing team with organic

00:17:04.079 --> 00:17:05.079
&gt;&gt;Bob Scowcroft: Awesome, awesome.

00:17:05.079 --> 00:17:11.690
&gt;&gt;Presenter 2: we're not quite there but,
and our meats and poultry are antibiotic and

00:17:11.690 --> 00:17:19.610
steroid free and, but what's the positive
argument about organics?

00:17:19.610 --> 00:17:27.050
Yes we want to avoid this and this but in
our culture where we're concerned about nutrition

00:17:27.050 --> 00:17:35.360
and optimizing your life and things like that,
is there a benefit to eating organic that

00:17:35.360 --> 00:17:38.590
